    "lower_court": null,
    "facts_of_the_case": "\u003Cp\u003EThis case was a challenge to Daugherty\u0027s contempt conviction. He failed to appear before a Senate committee investigating the failure of Daugherty\u0027s brother (Harry Daugherty, the former Attorney General)to prosecute wrongdoers in the Teapot Dome scandal.\u003C\/p\u003E\n",
    "question": "\u003Cp\u003EWas the Senate committee out-of-bounds in issuing its contempt order since the purpose of the investigation had nothing to do with the committee\u0027s legislative purpose?\u003C\/p\u003E\n",
    "conclusion": "\u003Cp\u003EThe Court upheld Daugherty\u0027s contempt conviction, establishing a presumption that congressional investigations have a legislative purpose. This presumption was not overcome by showing that the committee also had another purpose, such as exposure of wrongdoing. This presumption would later restrict the Court\u0027s hand in clear cases of congressional overreaching while investigating communists after World War II.\u003C\/p\u003E\n",
